#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:4
msgid "Safe Remote Purchases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:10
msgid ""
"This is example code for learning purposes. Do not use in production without "
"thorough review and testing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:12
msgid ""
"In this example, we have an escrow contract implementing a system for a "
"trustless transaction between a buyer and a seller. In this system, a seller "
"posts an item for sale and makes a deposit to the contract of twice the "
"item's ``value``. At this moment, the contract has a balance of 2 * "
"``value``. The seller can reclaim the deposit and close the sale as long as "
"a buyer has not yet made a purchase. If a buyer is interested in making a "
"purchase, they would make a payment and submit an equal amount for deposit "
"(totaling 2 * ``value``) into the contract and locking the contract from "
"further modification. At this moment, the contract has a balance of 4 * "
"``value`` and the seller would send the item to buyer. Upon the buyer's "
"receipt of the item, the buyer will mark the item as received in the "
"contract, thereby returning the buyer's deposit (not payment), releasing the "
"remaining funds to the seller, and completing the transaction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:25
msgid ""
"There are certainly other ways of designing a secure escrow system with less "
"overhead for both the buyer and seller, but for the purpose of this example, "
"we want to explore one way how an escrow system can be implemented "
"trustlessly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:29
msgid "Let's go!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:31
msgid ""
"#pragma version >0.3.10\n"
"\n"
"# Safe Remote Purchase\n"
"# Originally from\n"
"# https://github.com/ethereum/solidity/blob/develop/docs/solidity-by-example."
"rst\n"
"# Ported to vyper and optimized.\n"
"\n"
"# Rundown of the transaction:\n"
"# 1. Seller posts item for sale and posts safety deposit of double the item "
"value.\n"
"#    Balance is 2*value.\n"
"#    (1.1. Seller can reclaim deposit and close the sale as long as nothing "
"was purchased.)\n"
"# 2. Buyer purchases item (value) plus posts an additional safety deposit "
"(Item value).\n"
"#    Balance is 4*value.\n"
"# 3. Seller ships item.\n"
"# 4. Buyer confirms receiving the item. Buyer's deposit (value) is "
"returned.\n"
"#    Seller's deposit (2*value) + items value is returned. Balance is 0.\n"
"\n"
"value: public(uint256) #Value of the item\n"
"seller: public(address)\n"
"buyer: public(address)\n"
"unlocked: public(bool)\n"
"ended: public(bool)\n"
"finalized: public(bool)\n"
"\n"
"@deploy\n"
"@payable\n"
"def __init__():\n"
"    assert (msg.value % 2) == 0\n"
"    assert msg.value > 0\n"
"    self.value = msg.value // 2  # The seller initializes the contract by\n"
"        # posting a safety deposit of 2*value of the item up for sale.\n"
"    self.seller = msg.sender\n"
"    self.unlocked = True\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def abort():\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert self.unlocked #Is the contract still refundable?\n"
"    assert msg.sender == self.seller # Only the seller can refund\n"
"                                     # his deposit before any buyer "
"purchases the item.\n"
"    self.finalized = True\n"
"    assert self.balance > 0 and self.balance == 2 * self.value\n"
"    send(self.seller, self.balance)\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"@payable\n"
"def purchase():\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert self.unlocked # Is the contract still open (is the item still up\n"
"                         # for sale)?\n"
"    assert msg.value == (2 * self.value) # Is the deposit the correct "
"value?\n"
"    self.buyer = msg.sender\n"
"    self.unlocked = False\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def received():\n"
"    # 1. Conditions\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert not self.unlocked # Is the item already purchased and pending\n"
"                             # confirmation from the buyer?\n"
"    assert msg.sender == self.buyer\n"
"    assert not self.ended\n"
"\n"
"    # 2. Effects\n"
"    self.ended = True\n"
"    self.finalized = True\n"
"\n"
"    # 3. Interaction\n"
"    send(self.buyer, self.value) # Return the buyer's deposit (=value) to "
"the buyer.\n"
"    assert self.balance == 3 * self.value\n"
"    send(self.seller, self.balance) # Return the seller's deposit (=2*value) "
"and the\n"
"                                    # purchase price (=value) to the "
"seller.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:35
msgid ""
"This is also a moderately short contract, however a little more complex in "
"logic. Let's break down this contract bit by bit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:38
msgid ""
"value: public(uint256) #Value of the item\n"
"seller: public(address)\n"
"buyer: public(address)\n"
"unlocked: public(bool)\n"
"ended: public(bool)\n"
"finalized: public(bool)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:43
msgid ""
"Like the other contracts, we begin by declaring our global variables public "
"with their respective data types. Remember that the ``public`` function "
"allows the variables to be *readable* by an external caller, but not "
"*writeable*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:47
msgid ""
"@deploy\n"
"@payable\n"
"def __init__():\n"
"    assert (msg.value % 2) == 0\n"
"    assert msg.value > 0\n"
"    self.value = msg.value // 2  # The seller initializes the contract by\n"
"        # posting a safety deposit of 2*value of the item up for sale.\n"
"    self.seller = msg.sender\n"
"    self.unlocked = True\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:52
msgid ""
"With a ``@payable`` decorator on the constructor, the contract creator will "
"be required to make an initial deposit equal to twice the item's ``value`` "
"to initialize the contract, which will be later returned. This is in "
"addition to the gas fees needed to deploy the contract on the blockchain, "
"which is not returned. We ``assert`` that the deposit is divisible by 2 to "
"ensure that the seller deposited a valid amount. The constructor stores the "
"item's value in the contract variable ``self.value`` and saves the contract "
"creator into ``self.seller``. The contract variable ``self.unlocked`` is "
"initialized to ``True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:62
msgid ""
"@external\n"
"def abort():\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert self.unlocked #Is the contract still refundable?\n"
"    assert msg.sender == self.seller # Only the seller can refund\n"
"                                     # his deposit before any buyer "
"purchases the item.\n"
"    self.finalized = True\n"
"    assert self.balance > 0 and self.balance == 2 * self.value\n"
"    send(self.seller, self.balance)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:67
msgid ""
"The ``abort()`` method is a method only callable by the seller and while the "
"contract is still ``unlocked``—meaning it is callable only prior to any "
"buyer making a purchase. As we will see in the ``purchase()`` method that "
"when a buyer calls the ``purchase()`` method and sends a valid amount to the "
"contract, the contract will be locked and the seller will no longer be able "
"to call ``abort()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:74
msgid ""
"When the seller calls ``abort()`` and if the ``assert`` statements pass, the "
"contract sends the balance back to the seller, effectively canceling the "
"sale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:77
msgid ""
"@external\n"
"@payable\n"
"def purchase():\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert self.unlocked # Is the contract still open (is the item still up\n"
"                         # for sale)?\n"
"    assert msg.value == (2 * self.value) # Is the deposit the correct "
"value?\n"
"    self.buyer = msg.sender\n"
"    self.unlocked = False\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:82
msgid ""
"Like the constructor, the ``purchase()`` method has a ``@payable`` "
"decorator, meaning it can be called with a payment. For the buyer to make a "
"valid purchase, we must first ``assert`` that the contract's ``unlocked`` "
"property is ``True`` and that the amount sent is equal to twice the item's "
"value. We then set the buyer to the ``msg.sender`` and lock the contract. At "
"this point, the contract has a balance equal to 4 times the item value and "
"the seller must send the item to the buyer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:90
msgid ""
"@external\n"
"def received():\n"
"    # 1. Conditions\n"
"    assert not self.finalized\n"
"    assert not self.unlocked # Is the item already purchased and pending\n"
"                             # confirmation from the buyer?\n"
"    assert msg.sender == self.buyer\n"
"    assert not self.ended\n"
"\n"
"    # 2. Effects\n"
"    self.ended = True\n"
"    self.finalized = True\n"
"\n"
"    # 3. Interaction\n"
"    send(self.buyer, self.value) # Return the buyer's deposit (=value) to "
"the buyer.\n"
"    assert self.balance == 3 * self.value\n"
"    send(self.seller, self.balance) # Return the seller's deposit (=2*value) "
"and the\n"
"                                    # purchase price (=value) to the "
"seller.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:95
msgid ""
"Finally, upon the buyer's receipt of the item, the buyer can confirm their "
"receipt by calling the ``received()`` method to distribute the funds as "
"intended—where the seller receives 3/4 of the contract balance and the buyer "
"receives 1/4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vyper-by-example/safe-remote-purchase.rst:100
msgid ""
"By calling ``received()``, we begin by checking that the contract is indeed "
"locked, ensuring that a buyer had previously paid. We also ensure that this "
"method is only callable by the buyer. If these two ``assert`` statements "
"pass, we refund the buyer their initial deposit and send the seller the "
"remaining funds, completing the transaction."
msgstr ""

